{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d6de134d-3138-4c0f-a8da-c2897ffa8d74","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what brings workloads (like `maui`) back in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — re-installs the workloads you already have **at their current versions**. It fixes corrupted installations but won't pull newer versions needed by an updated SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:** Since your SDK moved forward, your workloads need to catch up. `update` does that; `repair` would just reinstall the old (now-incompatible) versions.\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf issues persist after updating, also try restoring workloads declared in your project:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload restore\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"095656df-767a-44ab-b982-8844cb640c85","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":275,"requestId":"1120:1FF93E:BE325E:DE4260:69FE84F6"},"id":"de665e98-7492-475e-8880-b6de9e086ddc","timestamp":"2026-05-09T00:51:20.971Z","parentId":"52140ea1-a91d-45e2-8abe-58558f9b2937"}
